Off By One Error — IndexError: list index out of range

1. Error Description
The Error Message
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "stock_manager.py", line 25, in <module>
    main()
  File "stock_manager.py", line 17, in main
    print_inventory_report(items)
  File "stock_manager.py", line 10, in print_inventory_report
    for i in range(len(items) + 1):
IndexError: list index out of range

The Broken Code
def print_inventory_report(items):
    for i in range(len(items) + 1):  # <-- the bug is here
        print(f"Item {i+1}: {items[i][name]} - Qty: {items[i][quantity]}")

def main():
    items = [
        {"name": "Laptop", "quantity": 15},
        {"name": "Mouse", "quantity": 30},
        {"name": "Keyboard", "quantity": 25}
    ]
    print_inventory_report(items)

What This Error Means in Plain English
The program tried to access position 3 in a list that only has positions 0, 1, and 2. Like reaching for a book on a shelf that does not exist.
Python lists are zero-indexed. A list with 3 items has valid positions 0, 1, and 2 only. Position 3 is empty, so Python crashes with IndexError.

Most Relevant Line in the Stack Trace
Always find YOUR filename in the stack trace first — that is where the bug lives:
File "stock_manager.py", line 10, in print_inventory_report
    for i in range(len(items) + 1):
Everything above this line is Python internal machinery. Your file is where the problem starts.

2. Root Cause Identification
Chain of Events Leading to the Error
Step	What Happened
1	main() creates items list with 3 items: Laptop, Mouse, Keyboard
2	Valid list indexes are 0, 1, 2 only
3	len(items) = 3, then + 1 makes it 4
4	range(4) produces: 0, 1, 2, 3
5	Loop runs fine for indexes 0, 1, 2
6	Loop tries index 3 — nothing there — CRASH

Visual Explanation
List:    [Laptop,  Mouse,   Keyboard]
Index:      0        1          2     <- only goes to 2!

range(len(items) + 1) = range(4) = [0, 1, 2, 3]
                                              ^
                          This index does not exist!

The entire error is caused by just two characters: + 1. Removing them completely fixes the bug.

3. Suggested Solutions
Fix 1 — Remove the + 1 (Simplest)
# BROKEN
for i in range(len(items) + 1):

# FIXED
for i in range(len(items)):
The loop now produces 0, 1, 2 — exactly matching the valid indexes.

Fix 2 — Use enumerate() (Recommended Best Practice)
for i, item in enumerate(items, start=1):
    print(f"Item {i}: {item[name]} - Quantity: {item[quantity]}")
enumerate() gives you both the index AND the item automatically. No manual index calculation means off-by-one errors become impossible.

Comparing All Three Approaches
Approach	Safety	Readability
range(len(items) + 1)	CRASHES	Poor — easy to make mistakes
range(len(items))	Works	OK — still manual indexing
enumerate(items, start=1)	Works	Best — no index math needed

