6. Final Error Analysis — Submission Format
Error Analysis: Off By One Error (IndexError)
Error Description
The program crashed trying to access list position 3 in a list that only has positions 0, 1, and 2. In plain English — it reached for a book on a shelf that does not exist. Python lists are zero-indexed, meaning a list with 3 items has valid positions 0, 1, and 2 only.

Root Cause
The + 1 in range(len(items) + 1) makes the loop run one step too far. With 3 items, range(4) produces 0, 1, 2, 3. The loop succeeds for 0, 1, and 2 then crashes on 3 because no item exists at that position.

Solution
# Option 1 — Minimum fix
for i in range(len(items)):

# Option 2 — Best practice
for i, item in enumerate(items, start=1):
    print(f"Item {i}: {item[name]} - Quantity: {item[quantity]}")

Learning Points
•	Python lists are zero-indexed — N items means indexes 0 to N-1, never N itself
•	Always find YOUR filename in a stack trace first — that is where your bug lives
•	enumerate() is safer than range(len()) and eliminates off-by-one errors completely
•	When you see IndexError, immediately check any range() calls for + 1 mistakes
•	This was a logic error, not a dependency issue — no pip commands were needed
•	Writing tests for empty lists and single items catches this type of bug early
